It was removed  immediately just hours after airing.  Having taken a lot of criticism and  numerous amount of death threats  the director s image as a professional  and visual artist was now being torn apart. Video_Title: Key & Peele Super Bowl Special - Marshawn Lynch and Richard Sherman's Joint Press Conference
Comment_Content: I m seeing a lot of  this wasn t funny  and  I didn t laugh . Key and Peele  are known to be very metaphorical through their skits  bringing up several  topics such as economic inequality  racial profiling and several other  political matters. I think it s fair to say the two have constructed an  easy outlet platform for their opinions to be represented in a manner that  isn t aggressively blatant and also allows for the viewer to create their  own opinions based on their interpretation. That s the way I see the Key    Peele skits. For this particular one I see a press conference full of  individuals sitting on the edge of their seats and lingering on every  single word the two are conjuring up. I interpret it as how so many people  in our culture and our society hold the words of the most talked about  celebrity or figure  so closely  no matter how unrelated to them personally  those words being spoken may be... But I could be totally wrong  it s an  interpretation  one of many I m sure. Seeing as these two are comedians   I m not necessarily saying that for the message you should give up the  laugh but I do think one can come out watching this with something  gained...

For those of you who don t understand this skit  It s pretty much making  fun of the  Modern Art  scene these days.  They were pretty much saying that no matter how stupid and ridiculous your  artwork is  you can slap a couple of words or even a story behind it and  SOMEONE is going buy into it and praise it for being so  deep  and   thought provoking . I know this from personal experience  I used to attend  an art college.  For example  there was a student in one of my art classes who did a  performance piece in which he slammed a chair on the floor for 10 minutes  straight. I kid you not  that was the only thing he did for 10 minutes.  After he finished  the student said  I wanted to capture the vicious  turmoil that rages in society today.  My teacher along with the entire  class erupted in applause.  I m thinking to myself  Am I missing something  here  all I saw was a chair being slammed continuously on the floor for 10  straight minutes. Maybe I m crazy.   Anyways  just thought I d share that to anyone who was confused about this  skit. Props to Key and Peele for doing this.

Arguably a portrayal of an oppositional allusion  to T  S  Eliots Modernist  masterpiece  The Waste Land   the experimental theatrical piece   Dicknanigans  is an avant garde play regarding the implications of a  dissolution of societal norms.  Furthermore   Dicknanigans   not only portrays the primitive savageness  that lies within us all but also the storminess and verisimilitude of  passion. The divisiveness of the ephemeral progression of the play acts a  metaphor to Shakespeare s  Measure for Measure  as the macabre  fleeting  nature of life is examined. In addition  the references to both  Shakespeare s and Eliots works are in fact a juxtaposition of how figures  can contribute to the culture of Western Society and analyze the growing  barrenness fragmentation of it. The violence is a satirical observation of  the growing restlessness of the millennial generation and is a  comment about how both pain and progress go hand in hand within our world.  The repetition of violence and  Dicknanigans  link violence  sexuality and  passion with one another to bring long harbored internal strife within our  society to the surface. The cognizance portrayed within this play is an  abstract view on realism  said cognizance is a hard counter to the  existential despair and nihilism within modern society and the exquisite  eucatastrophe is a refreshing and long overdue conclusion on the human  condition.
